TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Internal Morality of Contracting: Advancing the Contractualist Endeavor in Business Ethics
AU  - van Oosterhout, J. (Hans)
AU  - Heugens, Pursey P. M. A. R.
AU  - Kaptein, Muel
Y1  - 2006/07/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.21318915
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2006.21318915
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 521
EP  - 539
VL  - 31
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Integrative social contracts theory is arguably the most promising theory of business ethics to date, but often criticized for its inability to produce substantive, action-guiding norms. Rather than importing moral substance from outside the contractualist framework, or abandoning contractualist business ethics (CBE) altogether, we seek to advance CBE by exploring the internal morality of contracting. We demonstrate that substantive norms for guiding and constraining business conduct can be produced without relying on premises from outside the contractualist framework.
AB  - Integrative social contracts theory is arguably the most promising theory of business ethics to date, but often criticized for its inability to produce substantive, action-guiding norms. Rather than importing moral substance from outside the contractualist framework, or abandoning contractualist business ethics (CBE) altogether, we seek to advance CBE by exploring the internal morality of contracting. We demonstrate that substantive norms for guiding and constraining business conduct can be produced without relying on premises from outside the contractualist framework.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.21318915
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2006.21318915
Y2  - 2026/04/24
