TY  - JOUR
T1  - Orchestrating Innovation Networks
AU  - Dhanaraj, Charles
AU  - Parkhe, Arvind
Y1  - 2006/07/01
PY  - 2006
DA  - 2006/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2006.21318923
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2006.21318923
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 659
EP  - 669
VL  - 31
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Innovation networks can often be viewed as loosely coupled systems of autonomous firms. We propose that hub firms orchestrate network activities to ensure the creation and extraction of value, without the benefit of hierarchical authority. Orchestration comprises knowledge mobility, innovation appropriability, and network stability. We reject the view of network members as inert entities that merely respond to inducements and constraints arising from their network ties, and we embrace the essential player-structure duality present in networks.
AB  - Innovation networks can often be viewed as loosely coupled systems of autonomous firms. We propose that hub firms orchestrate network activities to ensure the creation and extraction of value, without the benefit of hierarchical authority. Orchestration comprises knowledge mobility, innovation appropriability, and network stability. We reject the view of network members as inert entities that merely respond to inducements and constraints arising from their network ties, and we embrace the essential player-structure duality present in networks.
